In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = new Window(new AppShell());

        window.Created   += (s, e) => Log("Created");
        window.Activated += (s, e) => Log("Activated");
        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Log("Deactivated");
        window.Stopped   += (s, e) => Log("Stopped");
        window.Resumed   += (s, e) => Log("Resumed");
        window.Destroying += (s, e) => Log("Destroying");
        // Fired when the back button is pressed (Android/Windows)
        window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Log("Backgrounding");

        return window;
    }

    static void Log(string evt)
        => System.Diagnostics.Debug.WriteLine($"[Window] {evt} at {DateTime.Now:T}");
}
```

**Typical transition order:**

| Action | Events fired |
|---|---|
| App launch | `Created → Activated` |
| User switches away | `Deactivated → Stopped` |
| User returns | `Resumed → Activated` |
| App closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |

> **Tip:** `Backgrounding` is the place to persist transient state (its `BackgroundingEventArgs` carries a `State` dictionary you can write to).
